<span id="freeTextContainer9385736729737219422">A young woman in California has lost her husband and now her house. The husband took off after just a couple of years of marriage. She lost the house due to a bureaucratic snafu about over-due taxes. She really didnâ€™t owe the taxes but she simply threw out mail without reading it, so now the house has been sold out from under her and auctioned off to an Iranian immigrant family. She can probably get it back but it will take years of litigation and lawyers she canâ€™t afford on her salary from clea</span>
  <span id="freeText9385736729737219422" style="display:none">A young woman in California has lost her husband and now her house. The husband took off after just a couple of years of marriage. She lost the house due to a bureaucratic snafu about over-due taxes. She really didnâ€™t owe the taxes but she simply threw out mail without reading it, so now the house has been sold out from under her and auctioned off to an Iranian immigrant family. She can probably get it back but it will take years of litigation and lawyers she canâ€™t afford on her salary from cleaning houses for a Merry Maids type outfit.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1494119446i/22686904._SX540_.jpg" width="330" height="220" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br> <br>As an ex-alcoholic and ex-cocaine user, sheâ€™s living in cheap motels and heading back into a downward spiral until she meets a local cop and they fall in love; he falls harder than she. But he brings two big problems: heâ€™s married with young kids and his idea of helping her is threatening the Iranians in various ways to get them to move out. He separates from his wife and they move into a friendâ€™s hunting cabin.<br><br>All three major characters are deeply flawed. Sheâ€™s a bundle of issues â€“ shall we say a hot mess? The bullying cop admits to previously framing a criminal by planting drugs on him (although for a good cause â€“ he was a wife-beater). The Iranian was a colonel under the Shah and although not in SAVAK he hung out with those guys so we know heâ€™s no prize. He is abusive to both his wife and son. And he is obsessed with making money off the eventual sale of the house so he refuses the countyâ€™s offer to give the house back with a refund of what he paid at auction. The young woman and the cop are very Trump-like in their attitudes toward the immigrants; more-or-less: â€œLook at them ARABS in their fancy cars in MY house playing FOREIGN music and speaking a FOREIGN language in their fancy clothesâ€ etc. The cop understands they are not â€œArabsâ€ but she never gets it.<br><br>Thereâ€™s some good writing, as in this description of a truck stop: â€œâ€¦dark place full of independent truckers coming off days on the road alone, men who wore their loneliness on their shirtsleeves like a badge in need of a polish.â€ Weâ€™re treated to a lot of pithy Iranian idioms: â€œâ€œif there is no snake at your feet, do not lift rocks at the side of the road.â€ I also think itâ€™s one of the best depictions I have read of the trauma a woman goes though in having an affair with a married man. <br><br>I recall this book coming out years ago (1999) and seeing it in the top-10 book rack at every supermarket and drug-store and thinking â€œthat looks interesting.â€ And it is, but itâ€™s also a bit slow in places. (Theyâ€™re going back to the cabin AGAIN? To rehash everything once more?) Still a good read as it heads toward its tragic ending. It was an Oprah pick and was made into a movie in 2003. <br><br>Photo from Zillow</span>
